{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"3876084a-c030-42be-a5c6-83ba03e874bb","content":"The standard approach is to **wrap file system calls behind an interface**:\n\n```csharp\npublic interface IFileSystem\n{\n    string ReadAllText(string path);\n    void WriteAllText(string path, string contents);\n    bool DirectoryExists(string path);\n}\n\npublic class PhysicalFileSystem : IFileSystem\n{\n    public string ReadAllText(string path) => File.ReadAllText(path);\n    public void WriteAllText(string path, string contents) => File.WriteAllText(path, contents);\n    public bool DirectoryExists(string path) => Directory.Exists(path);\n}\n```\n\nThen inject `IFileSystem` into classes that need it. In tests, mock it or use an in-memory implementation.\n\n**Alternatives:**\n\n- **`System.IO.Abstractions`** — popular NuGet package that provides `IFileSystem` out of the box with a mock file system for testing.\n- **Microsoft's `IFileProvider`** — read-only, useful if you only need to read files.\n\nThe NuGet package (`System.IO.Abstractions`) is usually the quickest path since it covers the entire `System.IO` surface and ships with `MockFileSystem` for tests.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"bb293aa1-0c9c-46c4-83b6-ac008f2f6616","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to make file system operations (`File.WriteAllText`, `File.ReadAllText`, `Directory.Exists`) testable in their .NET project. This is a design/architecture question rather than a code change request.\n\nThe standard approach is to abstract file system operations behind an interface, allowing you to mock them in tests. Let me give a concise answer.","outputTokens":385,"requestId":"BC5D:2EF3EB:20582E4:23BD030:69FA9BC9"},"id":"ec941399-bc4f-470f-b59a-8dda6570f5dc","timestamp":"2026-05-06T01:39:29.927Z","parentId":"bedefbd7-b438-4d04-bda7-f9943a569191"}
